00:01:00.806 --> 00:01:03.756 A:middle
But eventually, I
chose an area to work

00:01:03.756 --> 00:01:05.406 A:middle
on that was rather
unconventional.

00:01:05.556 --> 00:01:09.356 A:middle
I decided I wanted to work
with kids with disabilities.

00:01:09.536 --> 00:01:12.576 A:middle
I wanted to make assistive
technology for children

00:01:12.576 --> 00:01:17.116 A:middle
who had difficulties with
various kinds of disabilities.

00:01:18.576 --> 00:01:22.876 A:middle
Now the way I got into
this particular field --

00:01:23.356 --> 00:01:26.546 A:middle
when I went back
to India in 2008,

00:01:27.446 --> 00:01:28.696 A:middle
there was a friend of mine.

00:01:28.696 --> 00:01:32.376 A:middle
And she runs a school in the
city of Chennai in the south

00:01:32.376 --> 00:01:35.266 A:middle
of India, and it's
called Vidya Sagar.

00:01:36.496 --> 00:01:39.006 A:middle
Now, Vidya Sagar is
a special school.

00:01:39.006 --> 00:01:42.486 A:middle
It's a school for kids with
various kinds of disabilities --

00:01:42.486 --> 00:01:44.776 A:middle
cerebral palsy, autism.

00:01:45.696 --> 00:01:49.266 A:middle
And when my friend found
out that I was looking

00:01:49.266 --> 00:01:52.026 A:middle
for instant problems
to solve, she suggested

00:01:52.206 --> 00:01:55.796 A:middle
that I visit the school and
interact with the kids and see

00:01:55.796 --> 00:01:57.966 A:middle
if there was anything
that struck me.

00:01:59.496 --> 00:02:01.926 A:middle
So I went to Vidya
Sagar and I sat down


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:01:59.496 --> 00:02:01.926 A:middle
So I went to Vidya
Sagar and I sat down

00:02:01.926 --> 00:02:03.236 A:middle
and I met some of the kids.

00:02:04.506 --> 00:02:06.496 A:middle
Now that visit was
an eye-opener for me.

00:02:07.336 --> 00:02:10.286 A:middle
You know, I saw that these
kids were intelligent,

00:02:10.545 --> 00:02:13.086 A:middle
they were smart, they
were eager to learn,

00:02:13.146 --> 00:02:15.046 A:middle
they were enthusiastic,
they were social.

00:02:15.946 --> 00:02:18.296 A:middle
But the reason that they weren't

00:02:18.296 --> 00:02:20.876 A:middle
in a regular school was
primarily one reason.

00:02:21.776 --> 00:02:24.206 A:middle
And that was that they had
difficulty with communication.

00:02:25.856 --> 00:02:30.356 A:middle
Now, if you look at kids with
cerebral palsy, the main reason

00:02:30.356 --> 00:02:34.006 A:middle
that they can't communicate is
because the part of the brain

00:02:34.006 --> 00:02:36.786 A:middle
that process muscle
movements is impaired,

00:02:36.786 --> 00:02:38.516 A:middle
so they have difficulty
controlling all

00:02:38.516 --> 00:02:41.726 A:middle
of the different muscles that
are used to generate speech.

00:02:43.326 --> 00:02:45.696 A:middle
But with autism, it's actually
a very different story.

00:02:47.146 --> 00:02:49.746 A:middle
The first kid that I met
with autism was actually

00:02:49.746 --> 00:02:51.616 A:middle
at Vidya Sagar during
that visit.

00:02:52.106 --> 00:02:53.026 A:middle
His name was Santhosh.

00:02:54.256 --> 00:02:57.006 A:middle
Now I was sitting across
the table from Santhosh,

00:02:57.006 --> 00:02:59.466 A:middle
and Santhosh had a lot of
difficulty with a few things

00:02:59.466 --> 00:03:01.306 A:middle
that we take for granted.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:02:59.466 --> 00:03:01.306 A:middle
that we take for granted.

00:03:01.526 --> 00:03:05.276 A:middle
For example, he found it really
hard to read my body language.

00:03:06.156 --> 00:03:09.256 A:middle
He would find it really hard
to see my face and to make

00:03:09.256 --> 00:03:13.286 A:middle
out what kind of emotion I
was feeling at that time.

00:03:13.496 --> 00:03:15.116 A:middle
The other thing that
Santhosh had a lot

00:03:15.116 --> 00:03:16.756 A:middle
of difficulty with was language.

00:03:17.936 --> 00:03:20.766 A:middle
Because language is
fundamentally very symbolic.

00:03:21.076 --> 00:03:22.296 A:middle
You know, it's very abstract.

00:03:22.826 --> 00:03:24.626 A:middle
It's not something that
we realize every day,

00:03:24.626 --> 00:03:28.766 A:middle
but it's really one of the most
abstract things that we use.

00:03:29.346 --> 00:03:31.606 A:middle
We have all of these
different sound sequences,

00:03:31.606 --> 00:03:36.076 A:middle
all of these different words,
and these words are something

00:03:36.076 --> 00:03:38.976 A:middle
that we assign meaning
to almost arbitrarily.

00:03:40.396 --> 00:03:43.406 A:middle
For example, if I
said the word "dog",

00:03:44.426 --> 00:03:48.326 A:middle
the word "dog" doesn't
have anything to do

00:03:48.326 --> 00:03:51.306 A:middle
with the animal the way
that I pronounce the word,

00:03:51.306 --> 00:03:52.446 A:middle
the way that I write the word.

00:03:52.446 --> 00:03:54.246 A:middle
You would never be
able to figure

00:03:54.246 --> 00:03:56.806 A:middle
out that it actually refers
to this particular animal.

00:03:57.466 --> 00:04:01.316 A:middle
It's very much abstract sound
through which we've assigned,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:03:57.466 --> 00:04:01.316 A:middle
It's very much abstract sound
through which we've assigned,

00:04:01.866 --> 00:04:03.686 A:middle
you know, a convention
that we agree on.

00:04:04.416 --> 00:04:08.356 A:middle
And that's why someone
with autism has a lot

00:04:08.356 --> 00:04:09.356 A:middle
of difficulty with this.

00:04:09.466 --> 00:04:14.246 A:middle
Our brains have the ability to,
you know, encode and decode tens

00:04:14.246 --> 00:04:17.116 A:middle
of thousands of these
arbitrary sound sequences.

00:04:17.676 --> 00:04:21.555 A:middle
But kids with autism find
it a little too fuzzy

00:04:21.896 --> 00:04:22.926 A:middle
for their comfort.

00:04:24.236 --> 00:04:27.456 A:middle
So my friend who runs
this school, Vidya Sagar,

00:04:27.456 --> 00:04:30.536 A:middle
she wanted me to look at
this particular problem

00:04:30.536 --> 00:04:34.066 A:middle
and she wanted me to see if I
could come up with an invention

00:04:34.516 --> 00:04:36.816 A:middle
that could give a voice
to these children.

00:04:36.816 --> 00:04:39.736 A:middle
I thought that was a fascinating
problem to work on just

00:04:39.736 --> 00:04:40.996 A:middle
from a technology perspective.

00:04:41.546 --> 00:04:44.296 A:middle
I also thought it was a huge
opportunity in this case

00:04:44.296 --> 00:04:46.856 A:middle
because there were kids all
over India, and really all

00:04:46.856 --> 00:04:50.786 A:middle
over the world, who
needed something like this.

00:04:50.786 --> 00:04:53.916 A:middle
My starting point to
provide these kinds

00:04:53.916 --> 00:04:55.956 A:middle
of assistive technologies
was something

00:04:55.956 --> 00:04:59.336 A:middle
that had actually been
discovered in the 70s

00:04:59.336 --> 00:05:01.366 A:middle
and the 80s and was being
used quite effectively.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:04:59.336 --> 00:05:01.366 A:middle
and the 80s and was being
used quite effectively.

00:05:01.986 --> 00:05:05.346 A:middle
What people working with kids
with autism had discovered was

00:05:05.346 --> 00:05:09.536 A:middle
that many of them have extremely
strong visual intelligence.

00:05:09.696 --> 00:05:12.476 A:middle
So they have a lot of
difficulty with the abstractness

00:05:12.476 --> 00:05:14.196 A:middle
of language, but they
feel very comfortable

00:05:14.616 --> 00:05:16.446 A:middle
with the concreteness
of pictures.

00:05:17.116 --> 00:05:18.946 A:middle
They're able to remember
pictures.

00:05:18.946 --> 00:05:21.756 A:middle
They're able to recall pictures
much easier than they're able

00:05:21.756 --> 00:05:24.836 A:middle
to do with sound
or with alphabets.

00:05:26.076 --> 00:05:28.936 A:middle
Even in India, it wasn't
very uncommon to see kids

00:05:28.936 --> 00:05:30.726 A:middle
with books like these.

00:05:31.146 --> 00:05:34.726 A:middle
Picture books, picture charts,
picture bracelets sometimes

00:05:34.726 --> 00:05:36.036 A:middle
that they would wear
around their wrists.

00:05:36.556 --> 00:05:40.836 A:middle
And if they wanted to ask for a
specific object, if they wanted

00:05:40.836 --> 00:05:43.796 A:middle
to request for water for
example, they would point

00:05:43.876 --> 00:05:48.716 A:middle
to a picture of water in their
book and that would communicate

00:05:48.716 --> 00:05:50.056 A:middle
to other people that
they wanted water.

00:05:51.076 --> 00:05:56.806 A:middle
At that time in [inaudible]
America, in 2007 and 2008,

00:05:57.706 --> 00:06:01.816 A:middle
this concept was being used
quite effectively as part


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:05:57.706 --> 00:06:01.816 A:middle
this concept was being used
quite effectively as part

00:06:01.816 --> 00:06:04.366 A:middle
of these devices that
were being built.

00:06:04.886 --> 00:06:07.536 A:middle
And this is an example
of one of these devices.

00:06:08.086 --> 00:06:11.276 A:middle
This is a fairly -- you know,
these devices were pretty big.

00:06:11.276 --> 00:06:12.226 A:middle
They were pretty bulky.

00:06:12.766 --> 00:06:15.756 A:middle
They ran a special
software on them.

00:06:15.756 --> 00:06:17.086 A:middle
They were often custom-built,

00:06:17.086 --> 00:06:18.776 A:middle
and they were paid
for by insurance.

00:06:19.346 --> 00:06:20.876 A:middle
So they were pretty expensive.

00:06:20.926 --> 00:06:23.456 A:middle
This device, for example,
would have cost anywhere

00:06:23.646 --> 00:06:25.786 A:middle
between $5,000 to $10,000.

00:06:26.106 --> 00:06:29.046 A:middle
And that price point is
completely out of range

00:06:29.046 --> 00:06:32.236 A:middle
for even the most affluent
of parents in India.

00:06:32.906 --> 00:06:36.426 A:middle
But what was happening
with that in 2007,

00:06:36.426 --> 00:06:39.316 A:middle
for example, the
iPhone came out.

00:06:39.866 --> 00:06:42.136 A:middle
And that was the beginning
of the smartphone revolution.

00:06:42.406 --> 00:06:46.106 A:middle
Right? So it was possible
at that time, 2008,

00:06:46.756 --> 00:06:50.306 A:middle
to actually buy electronic
components off the shelf

00:06:50.306 --> 00:06:52.166 A:middle
which were being
used in smartphones,

00:06:52.536 --> 00:06:54.576 A:middle
in these touchscreen
devices all over the world.

00:06:55.086 --> 00:06:59.116 A:middle
And to assemble them together
to create a touchscreen tablet

00:06:59.476 --> 00:07:00.956 A:middle
for a fraction of the price just


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:06:59.476 --> 00:07:00.956 A:middle
for a fraction of the price just

00:07:00.956 --> 00:07:04.196 A:middle
for a few hundred
dollars instead of having

00:07:04.196 --> 00:07:06.336 A:middle
to create these things
from the ground-up.

00:07:06.856 --> 00:07:10.366 A:middle
So that became my strategy
going into this particular area.

00:07:11.066 --> 00:07:13.106 A:middle
I thought I would
create a special software

00:07:13.226 --> 00:07:16.266 A:middle
that they could use on top of
a device that we would build

00:07:16.266 --> 00:07:19.036 A:middle
from these smartphone
components,

00:07:19.496 --> 00:07:23.426 A:middle
and we would then use that
to give these children a way

00:07:23.426 --> 00:07:24.096 A:middle
to communicate.

00:07:25.246 --> 00:07:31.516 A:middle
So I took this strategy and
then I plunged into the field

00:07:31.516 --> 00:07:33.196 A:middle
of creating assistive
technology.

00:07:33.666 --> 00:07:38.686 A:middle
And I quickly came up with
a very interesting talent.

00:07:39.766 --> 00:07:43.716 A:middle
You know, those of you who've
worked on solving hard problems

00:07:43.716 --> 00:07:47.676 A:middle
for a specific class of people,
you know that the process

00:07:47.846 --> 00:07:49.596 A:middle
of coming up with these
solutions is actually

00:07:49.596 --> 00:07:50.256 A:middle
pretty standard.

00:07:51.036 --> 00:07:54.336 A:middle
You go to the field, you talk to
people, and you listen to them,

00:07:54.336 --> 00:07:55.266 A:middle
you see what they have to say.

00:07:56.136 --> 00:07:58.096 A:middle
You ideate to come up
with these prototypes

00:07:58.096 --> 00:08:02.356 A:middle
and you build these
things that you take


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:07:58.096 --> 00:08:02.356 A:middle
and you build these
things that you take

00:08:03.306 --> 00:08:05.586 A:middle
to the people whose
problems you want to solve.

00:08:05.986 --> 00:08:08.736 A:middle
And then you get their feedback,
and then you iterate a number

00:08:08.736 --> 00:08:09.996 A:middle
of different times
till you have something

00:08:09.996 --> 00:08:10.856 A:middle
that works beautifully.

00:08:11.246 --> 00:08:12.886 A:middle
You know, that process
is very standardized.

00:08:13.206 --> 00:08:16.556 A:middle
In my particular case though,
I had a very peculiar problem.

00:08:16.946 --> 00:08:20.396 A:middle
Because the very reason that we
were building this device was

00:08:20.396 --> 00:08:22.366 A:middle
because these children
couldn't communicate.

00:08:23.706 --> 00:08:25.416 A:middle
So it was a chicken-and-egg
problem.

00:08:25.586 --> 00:08:27.766 A:middle
You know, we were
very happy to go

00:08:27.766 --> 00:08:29.546 A:middle
and ask them what they thought

00:08:29.546 --> 00:08:31.086 A:middle
about the prototypes
we were creating.

00:08:31.906 --> 00:08:33.456 A:middle
But what would actually
happen is

00:08:33.456 --> 00:08:36.326 A:middle
that the kids would use the
prototype for maybe a minute,

00:08:36.466 --> 00:08:38.635 A:middle
two minutes, and then
they would walk away.

00:08:39.405 --> 00:08:41.586 A:middle
And we had no idea -- you
know, were they tired?

00:08:41.586 --> 00:08:42.436 A:middle
Were they bored?

00:08:42.876 --> 00:08:44.006 A:middle
You know, did they not like it?

00:08:44.265 --> 00:08:46.956 A:middle
Did they think it was
completely worthless?

00:08:47.446 --> 00:08:48.676 A:middle
Were we solving the
wrong problem?

00:08:49.646 --> 00:08:53.096 A:middle
So that was a frustration
that, you know,

00:08:53.096 --> 00:08:55.696 A:middle
we lived with for
several months.

00:08:55.826 --> 00:08:58.966 A:middle
You know, every developer --

00:08:58.966 --> 00:09:02.506 A:middle
I'm sure every one of you here
has a happy-customer story


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:08:58.966 --> 00:09:02.506 A:middle
I'm sure every one of you here
has a happy-customer story

00:09:02.506 --> 00:09:06.266 A:middle
that's very close to your
hearts and that you really love.

00:09:07.056 --> 00:09:12.256 A:middle
You know, in my particular case,
you know, there was this boy.

00:09:12.656 --> 00:09:14.906 A:middle
His name was Rohit.

00:09:14.906 --> 00:09:17.566 A:middle
Rohit was one of the
people that we were trying

00:09:17.566 --> 00:09:19.256 A:middle
out every single one
of our prototypes with.

00:09:19.256 --> 00:09:22.026 A:middle
And one day, he came
into the room

00:09:22.026 --> 00:09:23.716 A:middle
where we were trying
out the prototype.

00:09:23.716 --> 00:09:25.926 A:middle
And I could see --
you know, on that day,

00:09:25.926 --> 00:09:28.196 A:middle
I could see the determination
in his face.

00:09:28.686 --> 00:09:30.436 A:middle
He was going to communicate
with me.

00:09:30.436 --> 00:09:35.056 A:middle
He was completely -- he had
that look of grim determination

00:09:35.326 --> 00:09:37.336 A:middle
as he walked into the room.

00:09:37.336 --> 00:09:40.136 A:middle
And, you know, I gave
him the newest prototype.

00:09:40.136 --> 00:09:42.286 A:middle
And I sat there, waiting
with anticipation.

00:09:43.606 --> 00:09:45.976 A:middle
And Rohit actually took
the device that I built.

00:09:46.366 --> 00:09:48.906 A:middle
Very painstakingly,
over several minutes,

00:09:49.576 --> 00:09:51.296 A:middle
he tapped on various buttons.

00:09:52.366 --> 00:09:54.946 A:middle
And then the device
said, "This sucks."

00:09:55.516 --> 00:09:58.516 A:middle
[ Laugther ]

00:09:59.516 --> 00:10:03.726 A:middle
[ Applause ]


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:09:59.516 --> 00:10:03.726 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:10:04.226 --> 00:10:08.836 A:middle
It's not exactly the kind
of testimonial that is put

00:10:08.836 --> 00:10:11.396 A:middle
up on your website, but
it was music to my ears.

00:10:11.396 --> 00:10:11.976 A:middle
Believe me.

00:10:13.136 --> 00:10:15.786 A:middle
Because from that point onwards,
the going was much faster.

00:10:15.856 --> 00:10:18.446 A:middle
You know, we could convince him

00:10:18.446 --> 00:10:19.916 A:middle
to tell us exactly
what he liked,

00:10:19.916 --> 00:10:21.036 A:middle
exactly what he didn't like.

00:10:22.036 --> 00:10:26.396 A:middle
And within a few months,
we'd come up with a device

00:10:26.396 --> 00:10:29.036 A:middle
that met Rohit's expectations.

00:10:30.286 --> 00:10:32.806 A:middle
And that was the device that
we launched to the market.

00:10:33.076 --> 00:10:34.076 A:middle
We called it Avaz.

00:10:34.416 --> 00:10:36.536 A:middle
Avaz is the Hindi
word for "voice".

00:10:36.536 --> 00:10:39.606 A:middle
It also means similar things
in many other languages.

00:10:40.046 --> 00:10:41.976 A:middle
Let me show you the device
that we actually built.

00:10:52.636 --> 00:10:58.556 A:middle
So this was the first prototype
that was ready for release,

00:10:58.556 --> 00:11:01.926 A:middle
the first product that
we built off Avaz.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

