the first product that
we built off Avaz.

00:11:02.356 --> 00:11:05.756 A:middle
It's the big, bulky,
black metal box,

00:11:05.756 --> 00:11:08.856 A:middle
and it's stuffed
with electronics.

00:11:09.176 --> 00:11:11.676 A:middle
You know, you could
mount it on a wheelchair.

00:11:11.676 --> 00:11:13.386 A:middle
You could put it on a desk.

00:11:14.196 --> 00:11:17.386 A:middle
Along with its wheelchair mount,
it weighed about 8 pounds,

00:11:17.706 --> 00:11:18.606 A:middle
so it was pretty heavy.

00:11:19.146 --> 00:11:21.566 A:middle
It had about an hour
of battery life.

00:11:21.566 --> 00:11:26.086 A:middle
You know, there was a really
embarrassing thing that happened

00:11:26.086 --> 00:11:28.066 A:middle
on the day that we were
supposed to launch this.

00:11:28.066 --> 00:11:30.906 A:middle
We kept it on a desk, and a
kid accidentally pushed it

00:11:30.906 --> 00:11:31.956 A:middle
down with his hand.

00:11:32.486 --> 00:11:34.656 A:middle
And it fell down on the
floor and it broke one

00:11:34.656 --> 00:11:35.676 A:middle
of the tiles on the floor.

00:11:36.516 --> 00:11:42.566 A:middle
[ Laugther ]

00:11:43.066 --> 00:11:44.126 A:middle
That was how heavy it was.

00:11:45.396 --> 00:11:48.646 A:middle
You know, as a concession to
safety, among other things,

00:11:49.426 --> 00:11:52.706 A:middle
we replaced the case
with plastic.

00:11:53.326 --> 00:12:02.586 A:middle
So that's the final version
of Avaz that we put out.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:11:53.326 --> 00:12:02.586 A:middle
So that's the final version
of Avaz that we put out.

00:12:02.626 --> 00:12:09.056 A:middle
This device costs about $600
-- 30,000 Indian rupees.

00:12:09.556 --> 00:12:12.456 A:middle
And at that price, it was
about 1/10 of the price

00:12:12.456 --> 00:12:14.676 A:middle
of similar dedicated
devices that were

00:12:14.676 --> 00:12:17.306 A:middle
in the market at that time.

00:12:17.306 --> 00:12:18.946 A:middle
And it was a breakthrough
in India.

00:12:18.946 --> 00:12:22.076 A:middle
It was the very first time that
anyone had created a device

00:12:22.076 --> 00:12:24.526 A:middle
for speech-assistive
technology in India.

00:12:25.206 --> 00:12:28.206 A:middle
And almost immediately
after we had it out there,

00:12:28.696 --> 00:12:31.236 A:middle
we started getting orders
from all over the country.

00:12:31.406 --> 00:12:34.266 A:middle
You know, every special
school in India wrote to us

00:12:34.266 --> 00:12:37.036 A:middle
and they wanted to know how they
could get their hands on Avaz

00:12:37.036 --> 00:12:38.076 A:middle
and how they could use it.

00:12:39.196 --> 00:12:41.736 A:middle
But Avaz was still a
very niche product.

00:12:41.736 --> 00:12:44.266 A:middle
I mean, it's meant for the
very specific niche of people

00:12:44.266 --> 00:12:46.746 A:middle
that have these particular
disabilities.

00:12:47.286 --> 00:12:52.606 A:middle
So we had this -- you know,
making dedicated hardware

00:12:52.656 --> 00:12:55.806 A:middle
in these small volumes
is always a challenge.

00:12:56.346 --> 00:12:58.216 A:middle
So even though the
response was fantastic,

00:12:58.216 --> 00:12:59.586 A:middle
even though we got
a lot of interest,

00:12:59.586 --> 00:13:01.406 A:middle
and even though this was
really helping the kids


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:12:59.586 --> 00:13:01.406 A:middle
and even though this was
really helping the kids

00:13:01.466 --> 00:13:05.686 A:middle
that we were intending
this to help, you know,

00:13:05.686 --> 00:13:07.116 A:middle
the more devices
we were selling,

00:13:07.246 --> 00:13:09.526 A:middle
the more money we were losing
just because we were spending

00:13:09.526 --> 00:13:12.036 A:middle
so much money in creating these
devices in the first place.

00:13:13.876 --> 00:13:15.706 A:middle
You know, we were
struggling to figure

00:13:15.706 --> 00:13:18.106 A:middle
out how we could make
the business sustainable.

00:13:18.106 --> 00:13:24.066 A:middle
And then in 2010, the
big news happened.

00:13:24.806 --> 00:13:27.416 A:middle
Steve Jobs announced the iPad.

00:13:28.056 --> 00:13:30.606 A:middle
And that was the start
of the tablet revolution.

00:13:30.606 --> 00:13:34.266 A:middle
But it also was a revolution
in the fortunes of my startup

00:13:35.186 --> 00:13:37.976 A:middle
because we saw this as a
way of getting ourselves

00:13:37.976 --> 00:13:41.136 A:middle
out of this hardware corner
that we painted ourselves into

00:13:41.776 --> 00:13:45.946 A:middle
and being able to make
these devices reach people,

00:13:46.096 --> 00:13:48.376 A:middle
making this application
reach people without having

00:13:48.376 --> 00:13:49.756 A:middle
to make the devices to do that.

00:13:50.846 --> 00:13:52.776 A:middle
So, in 2010, my team

00:13:52.776 --> 00:13:55.586 A:middle
and I started learning
how to code for iOS.

00:13:55.966 --> 00:14:02.926 A:middle
And in 2011, we launched the
first version of the Avaz App.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:13:55.966 --> 00:14:02.926 A:middle
And in 2011, we launched the
first version of the Avaz App.

00:14:03.206 --> 00:14:06.266 A:middle
Now the core functionality

00:14:06.266 --> 00:14:10.706 A:middle
of Avaz actually remains
the same today, you know,

00:14:10.706 --> 00:14:12.746 A:middle
compared to the first version

00:14:12.746 --> 00:14:14.916 A:middle
that we launched
way back in 2011.

00:14:14.916 --> 00:14:17.976 A:middle
And let me show you a
quick demo of how it works.

00:14:28.046 --> 00:14:28.786 A:middle
So this is Avaz.

00:14:29.076 --> 00:14:32.096 A:middle
And you can see that
it's essentially a bunch

00:14:32.096 --> 00:14:33.086 A:middle
of different pictures.

00:14:33.206 --> 00:14:36.896 A:middle
So there's pictures in here,
and there are pictures in each

00:14:36.896 --> 00:14:38.166 A:middle
of these different categories.

00:14:39.136 --> 00:14:41.846 A:middle
So there are literally thousands
of pictures in the app.

00:14:42.126 --> 00:14:45.836 A:middle
And a parent, or a teacher,
or a therapist could go in

00:14:45.836 --> 00:14:48.486 A:middle
and add words from the
child's life with photographs

00:14:48.686 --> 00:14:50.166 A:middle
from the child's life as well.

00:14:50.876 --> 00:14:52.896 A:middle
And the way that Avaz
works for a child

00:14:52.896 --> 00:14:54.316 A:middle
with a disability
is very simple.

00:14:54.316 --> 00:14:59.386 A:middle
A child would be able to recall
and remember these pictures.

00:14:59.906 --> 00:15:01.706 A:middle
And every time they
tap the picture.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:14:59.906 --> 00:15:01.706 A:middle
And every time they
tap the picture.

00:15:02.446 --> 00:15:02.526 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I

00:15:03.396 --> 00:15:04.456 A:middle
&gt;&gt; It will speak that out.

00:15:04.526 --> 00:15:07.006 A:middle
And they would be able to
sequence pictures together.

00:15:07.216 --> 00:15:07.606 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Feel

00:15:08.206 --> 00:15:11.106 A:middle
&gt;&gt; This way, and they could go
into these different categories.

00:15:11.216 --> 00:15:13.856 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Describe feelings.

00:15:14.106 --> 00:15:16.076 A:middle
&gt;&gt; And they could pick
different pictures out.

00:15:16.076 --> 00:15:17.236 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Excited

00:15:17.586 --> 00:15:19.246 A:middle
&gt;&gt; To be able to
create sentences.

00:15:19.996 --> 00:15:21.426 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I feel excited.

00:15:21.426 --> 00:15:23.646 A:middle
&gt;&gt; And then the app
would speak that out.

00:15:25.366 --> 00:15:28.906 A:middle
So that's Avaz -- essentially,
a bunch of different pictures

00:15:29.296 --> 00:15:32.536 A:middle
with a picture vocabulary that
helps children communicate.

00:15:32.956 --> 00:15:38.086 A:middle
So Avaz was literally
an artificial voice

00:15:38.576 --> 00:15:39.896 A:middle
for kids with disabilities.

00:15:42.096 --> 00:15:48.306 A:middle
You know, when we put Avaz
out in the field in India,

00:15:49.576 --> 00:15:51.536 A:middle
it was immediately
a game-changer

00:15:51.696 --> 00:15:52.536 A:middle
in many different ways.

00:15:53.256 --> 00:15:56.176 A:middle
For this kid, Rohit,
who had worked with us

00:15:56.176 --> 00:16:00.216 A:middle
to build Avaz, he
grew to love Avaz.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:15:56.176 --> 00:16:00.216 A:middle
to build Avaz, he
grew to love Avaz.

00:16:00.476 --> 00:16:03.846 A:middle
You know, he grew to be
able to customize and use it

00:16:03.846 --> 00:16:07.536 A:middle
so effectively that that same
year that we launched the app,

00:16:08.006 --> 00:16:12.396 A:middle
he went on to use Avaz to write
his exams and to finish school

00:16:12.616 --> 00:16:15.386 A:middle
and to go on to college.

00:16:15.536 --> 00:16:18.416 A:middle
You know, the media all over
India picked up the story

00:16:18.836 --> 00:16:20.556 A:middle
of this kid who'd
finished his exams

00:16:20.556 --> 00:16:21.986 A:middle
with an assistive-technology
device.

00:16:22.436 --> 00:16:23.666 A:middle
And not just this kid.

00:16:23.756 --> 00:16:25.636 A:middle
You know, they started
picking up stories from all

00:16:25.636 --> 00:16:29.576 A:middle
over the country about who kids
who had used Avaz to do things.

00:16:30.136 --> 00:16:33.996 A:middle
And even to this day, I think
Avaz has shaped the narrative

00:16:34.496 --> 00:16:36.776 A:middle
around these disabilities
in Indian media.

00:16:37.186 --> 00:16:38.926 A:middle
People started concentrating
less

00:16:38.926 --> 00:16:42.306 A:middle
on what these children could
not do and more on the abilities

00:16:42.306 --> 00:16:43.866 A:middle
of these children and
what they could do.

00:16:44.366 --> 00:16:48.676 A:middle
So that's one of the things that
Avaz has accomplished in India.

00:16:48.676 --> 00:16:49.856 A:middle
My personal favorite --

00:16:51.516 --> 00:16:57.066 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:16:57.566 --> 00:16:59.776 A:middle
My personal favorite anecdote

00:16:59.776 --> 00:17:03.286 A:middle
about Avaz users is actually
something that happened back


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:16:59.776 --> 00:17:03.286 A:middle
about Avaz users is actually
something that happened back

00:17:03.286 --> 00:17:04.836 A:middle
in the school where
this all started,

00:17:04.836 --> 00:17:07.606 A:middle
in the school of Vidya Sagar.

00:17:07.606 --> 00:17:09.935 A:middle
You know, the children at Vidya
Sagar, every year they put

00:17:09.935 --> 00:17:13.546 A:middle
up this play for the parents

00:17:13.546 --> 00:17:14.876 A:middle
and for the well-wishers
of the school.

00:17:15.705 --> 00:17:17.685 A:middle
And it just so happens
that, you know, every year,

00:17:17.685 --> 00:17:22.566 A:middle
it was almost a convention that
the lead roles in this play,

00:17:22.796 --> 00:17:25.705 A:middle
the most important roles,
would go to the kids

00:17:25.705 --> 00:17:27.616 A:middle
who could speak -- I
mean, the verbal children.

00:17:28.146 --> 00:17:28.766 A:middle
And the presence

00:17:28.766 --> 00:17:32.346 A:middle
of the nonverbal children was
very subdued in this event.

00:17:33.686 --> 00:17:35.746 A:middle
The year we put out Avaz,

00:17:35.986 --> 00:17:38.536 A:middle
the principal made this
incredibly bold decision.

00:17:39.426 --> 00:17:43.816 A:middle
He said, "This year, all of the
parts are going to go to kids

00:17:43.816 --> 00:17:46.096 A:middle
who can't speak,
and they're going

00:17:46.096 --> 00:17:48.386 A:middle
to deliver their
dialogues with Avaz."

00:17:49.196 --> 00:17:53.886 A:middle
You know, I was sitting in
the front row on the day

00:17:53.886 --> 00:17:55.066 A:middle
that that play was going on.

00:17:55.386 --> 00:17:58.386 A:middle
You know, I was extensively
a special guest.

00:17:58.426 --> 00:18:00.776 A:middle
But really, the principal
expected me to jump


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:17:58.426 --> 00:18:00.776 A:middle
But really, the principal
expected me to jump

00:18:00.776 --> 00:18:03.486 A:middle
up on the stage and fix things
if something didn't work.

00:18:04.041 --> 00:18:06.041 A:middle
[ Laughter ]

00:18:06.066 --> 00:18:07.986 A:middle
But I was sitting in the
front row right there.

00:18:09.186 --> 00:18:10.956 A:middle
And the atmosphere
was incredible.

00:18:10.956 --> 00:18:11.916 A:middle
It was electric.

00:18:12.556 --> 00:18:15.516 A:middle
You know, I could see how much
fun these kids were having

00:18:15.886 --> 00:18:19.386 A:middle
delivering their dialogues and
doing all of their, you know,

00:18:19.386 --> 00:18:20.916 A:middle
all of their actions
and everything.

00:18:21.156 --> 00:18:24.156 A:middle
And I turn back and I looked at
the parents of these children,

00:18:24.896 --> 00:18:26.396 A:middle
and they had tears
in their eyes.

00:18:26.396 --> 00:18:29.416 A:middle
You know, this was
the very first time

00:18:29.506 --> 00:18:31.876 A:middle
that these kids were
able to participate

00:18:31.876 --> 00:18:34.416 A:middle
in this quintessential
school experience

00:18:34.706 --> 00:18:36.916 A:middle
of being a part of
a school play.

00:18:37.296 --> 00:18:40.506 A:middle
And at that moment, I think it
sank into many of those parents

00:18:40.926 --> 00:18:43.366 A:middle
about how transformational
this device would be

00:18:43.526 --> 00:18:46.506 A:middle
in the lives of these kids.

00:18:47.516 --> 00:18:54.556 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:18:55.056 --> 00:18:56.836 A:middle
Another really important
moment in the history

00:18:56.926 --> 00:18:59.936 A:middle
of Avaz happened a little
later, a few months later.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:19:00.526 --> 00:19:04.136 A:middle
We got a call -- you know,
our customer support person --

00:19:04.266 --> 00:19:06.706 A:middle
she got a call from a
parent in central India.

00:19:06.806 --> 00:19:09.766 A:middle
You know, so this
parent called her up.

00:19:09.766 --> 00:19:13.086 A:middle
And this call was actually --
it played out very differently

00:19:13.086 --> 00:19:14.476 A:middle
from most of the
calls that we get,

00:19:14.626 --> 00:19:15.726 A:middle
you know, for customer support.

00:19:16.266 --> 00:19:20.106 A:middle
This lady had bought
Avaz for her son.

00:19:20.106 --> 00:19:21.326 A:middle
And, you know, she wanted

00:19:21.326 --> 00:19:22.666 A:middle
to know a bunch of
different things.

00:19:22.786 --> 00:19:26.586 A:middle
You know, she wanted to know
how she could assess her son

00:19:26.696 --> 00:19:28.956 A:middle
for whether this device
was suitable for the son,

00:19:28.956 --> 00:19:31.566 A:middle
and she wanted to know how
to set it up for her son.

00:19:32.476 --> 00:19:34.946 A:middle
She wanted to know how to
integrate it into his lessons.

00:19:34.946 --> 00:19:37.276 A:middle
She wanted to know how to
set up curriculum around it.

00:19:37.276 --> 00:19:39.326 A:middle
She wanted to know how
she could track progress,

00:19:39.826 --> 00:19:40.876 A:middle
you know, over the months.

00:19:41.416 --> 00:19:43.036 A:middle
She essentially wanted
to know how

00:19:43.036 --> 00:19:45.246 A:middle
to implement the
app for her son.

00:19:45.996 --> 00:19:51.836 A:middle
Now this is actually a pretty
atypical question that we get.

00:19:51.836 --> 00:19:55.476 A:middle
Because in most installations
of Avaz that we've seen,

00:19:56.106 --> 00:19:59.066 A:middle
a speech therapist would be
the person that would work

00:19:59.066 --> 00:20:02.656 A:middle
with the kid in order to
implement the app for them.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:19:59.066 --> 00:20:02.656 A:middle
with the kid in order to
implement the app for them.

00:20:02.886 --> 00:20:04.076 A:middle
So the speech therapist
would meet

00:20:04.076 --> 00:20:06.266 A:middle
with the kid maybe once a week,
they would do assessments,

00:20:06.266 --> 00:20:07.496 A:middle
they would do all of
these different things.

00:20:08.256 --> 00:20:09.746 A:middle
And so we asked this lady,

00:20:09.746 --> 00:20:11.886 A:middle
"Why don't you ask your speech
therapist these questions?

00:20:11.886 --> 00:20:15.396 A:middle
You know, that person is
probably much more qualified

00:20:15.496 --> 00:20:17.026 A:middle
to give you an answer to
some of these things."

00:20:18.086 --> 00:20:18.786 A:middle
On that day, I found

00:20:18.786 --> 00:20:22.916 A:middle
out something very
interesting about India.

00:20:23.256 --> 00:20:25.746 A:middle
This lady's son didn't
have a speech therapist.

00:20:26.936 --> 00:20:28.986 A:middle
In fact, the closest
speech therapist

00:20:29.286 --> 00:20:32.006 A:middle
to that lady was 300 miles away.

00:20:33.316 --> 00:20:35.346 A:middle
If she had to find a speech
therapist for her son,

00:20:35.346 --> 00:20:37.806 A:middle
she'd have to get on a
train, travel for six hours,

00:20:38.256 --> 00:20:41.726 A:middle
and go to a speech
therapist and come back home.

00:20:41.936 --> 00:20:43.026 A:middle
In fact, I'll tell you this.

00:20:43.406 --> 00:20:44.916 A:middle
In the entire country of India,

00:20:45.056 --> 00:20:47.136 A:middle
the country of 1.3
billion people,

00:20:48.256 --> 00:20:50.506 A:middle
there are 1,800 speech
therapists.

00:20:51.636 --> 00:20:53.846 A:middle
You could take all of the
speech therapists in India

00:20:53.846 --> 00:20:55.726 A:middle
and you could put
them in this room,

00:20:55.726 --> 00:20:58.466 A:middle
and you could fill this room
three times over with the number

00:20:58.466 --> 00:20:59.816 A:middle
of speech therapists
that are in India.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:21:01.736 --> 00:21:04.956 A:middle
So this was a mind-blowing
moment for us.

00:21:04.956 --> 00:21:07.056 A:middle
This was really an
eye-opening moment for us.

00:21:07.056 --> 00:21:10.856 A:middle
And what we had to do eventually
was that we had to take the app,

00:21:10.926 --> 00:21:14.486 A:middle
Avaz, and we had to build this
complete new app inside it.

00:21:14.486 --> 00:21:17.036 A:middle
So it's almost like a
sub-app within Avaz.

00:21:17.636 --> 00:21:18.916 A:middle
And what that sub-app did --

00:21:18.986 --> 00:21:21.676 A:middle
it was a pretty new
idea at that time.

00:21:21.676 --> 00:21:25.156 A:middle
What that sub-app did was
that it trained a parent

00:21:25.586 --> 00:21:27.926 A:middle
to be a therapist
for their child.

00:21:28.336 --> 00:21:30.546 A:middle
That was the only way that we
could get over this problem.

00:21:30.666 --> 00:21:32.076 A:middle
You know, as a startup,

00:21:32.076 --> 00:21:36.026 A:middle
we couldn't train the 5 million
therapists that India needs.

00:21:36.626 --> 00:21:39.486 A:middle
But this was actually more
transformational in my opinion

00:21:39.486 --> 00:21:42.726 A:middle
than even Avaz itself because
we were not just giving a device

00:21:42.726 --> 00:21:46.256 A:middle
for the child, we were actually
building up the resource base

00:21:46.866 --> 00:21:50.206 A:middle
for these children to get
high-quality intervention,

00:21:50.646 --> 00:21:56.666 A:middle
and from the people that these
children mattered the most

00:21:56.886 --> 00:21:58.676 A:middle
to -- to their parents.

00:21:58.676 --> 00:22:01.186 A:middle
So this happened, you
know, in 2011 shortly


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:21:58.676 --> 00:22:01.186 A:middle
So this happened, you
know, in 2011 shortly

00:22:01.186 --> 00:22:02.866 A:middle
after we brought Avaz out.

00:22:02.866 --> 00:22:05.856 A:middle
And shortly after
that, I won an award

00:22:05.856 --> 00:22:06.906 A:middle
from the President of India.

00:22:07.836 --> 00:22:09.976 A:middle
I had less facial
hair back then.

00:22:10.066 --> 00:22:12.066 A:middle
[ Laughter ]

00:22:12.116 --> 00:22:13.636 A:middle
But even more rewarding
than this --

00:22:13.636 --> 00:22:16.096 A:middle
you know, after five
years of lobbying --

00:22:17.196 --> 00:22:22.496 A:middle
this year, at long last, one of
the big states in India decided

00:22:22.496 --> 00:22:26.846 A:middle
to buy iPads, install Avaz on
them, and to give them away

00:22:26.846 --> 00:22:29.236 A:middle
to every school that they
supported in the state.

00:22:30.516 --> 00:22:34.546 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:22:35.046 --> 00:22:36.646 A:middle
This is the very first time

00:22:36.716 --> 00:22:41.386 A:middle
that the Indian government has
invested in assistive technology

00:22:41.386 --> 00:22:43.216 A:middle
for kids with speech
disabilities,

00:22:43.216 --> 00:22:45.846 A:middle
the very first time that the
Indian government has invested

00:22:45.846 --> 00:22:46.876 A:middle
in this stuff.

00:22:46.876 --> 00:22:49.126 A:middle
And in fact, the Apple guy
that's handling this order,

00:22:49.126 --> 00:22:51.646 A:middle
the guy at Apple that was
coordinating the delivery

00:22:51.646 --> 00:22:53.216 A:middle
of these devices, he told me

00:22:53.216 --> 00:22:55.856 A:middle
that this was the
largest-ever government order

00:22:56.216 --> 00:22:57.366 A:middle
of iPads in India.

00:22:58.046 --> 00:22:58.496 A:middle
And it's

00:22:58.496 --> 00:23:00.416 A:middle
for an assistive-technology
application.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:22:58.496 --> 00:23:00.416 A:middle
for an assistive-technology
application.

00:23:00.416 --> 00:23:01.056 A:middle
How cool is that?

00:23:01.356 --> 00:23:02.976 A:middle
For an assistive-technology
application.

00:23:03.516 --> 00:23:08.916 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:23:09.416 --> 00:23:11.766 A:middle
Today, there are
about 30,000 kids

00:23:11.766 --> 00:23:14.896 A:middle
around the world whose lives
have been touched by Avaz.

00:23:14.896 --> 00:23:16.326 A:middle
Avaz is an artificial voice

00:23:16.326 --> 00:23:17.936 A:middle
for 30,000 children
around the world.

00:23:18.996 --> 00:23:22.466 A:middle
You know, at these
scales -- 30,000 users --

00:23:23.196 --> 00:23:25.566 A:middle
we could see some very
interesting patterns

00:23:25.566 --> 00:23:27.016 A:middle
in the way that Avaz was used.

00:23:27.596 --> 00:23:29.006 A:middle
And let me talk to
you a little bit

00:23:29.006 --> 00:23:32.356 A:middle
about how Avaz was being
used around the world.

00:23:34.756 --> 00:23:37.096 A:middle
What Avaz did very
successfully was

00:23:37.096 --> 00:23:40.346 A:middle
to help kids have this
alternate access to words.

00:23:40.346 --> 00:23:43.116 A:middle
So instead of having to speak
them out, instead of having

00:23:43.116 --> 00:23:45.436 A:middle
to remember how they sounded,

00:23:45.436 --> 00:23:47.186 A:middle
they could use pictures
to communicate.

00:23:47.186 --> 00:23:50.966 A:middle
So, for example, if a kid wanted
to say that they were hungry

00:23:50.966 --> 00:23:53.766 A:middle
and they wanted something to
eat, they could go into the app

00:23:53.766 --> 00:23:55.226 A:middle
and find the word
"eat" and tap on it.

00:23:56.216 --> 00:23:58.396 A:middle
If they wanted to say that they
wanted to go to the bathroom,

00:23:58.396 --> 00:24:00.236 A:middle
for example, they
could go into the app


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:23:58.396 --> 00:24:00.236 A:middle
for example, they
could go into the app

00:24:00.316 --> 00:24:01.326 A:middle
and find the word "toilet".

00:24:01.846 --> 00:24:03.536 A:middle
If they were eating something

00:24:03.536 --> 00:24:06.786 A:middle
and they found the food
incredibly gross, they could go

00:24:06.786 --> 00:24:08.686 A:middle
into the app and they
could find the word "yucky"

00:24:08.686 --> 00:24:12.556 A:middle
and they could say that.

00:24:12.556 --> 00:24:16.086 A:middle
The problem happened when
kids had to communicate

00:24:16.236 --> 00:24:18.176 A:middle
with more than one word.

00:24:19.296 --> 00:24:23.366 A:middle
So, for example, if a kid
had to say, "I want water,"

00:24:24.066 --> 00:24:26.676 A:middle
it was quite common that
they would pick the word

00:24:26.676 --> 00:24:28.796 A:middle
"water" first and then they
would pick the word "want".

00:24:30.196 --> 00:24:32.436 A:middle
And they would do
it right sometimes.

00:24:32.436 --> 00:24:33.516 A:middle
They would do it
wrong sometimes.

00:24:33.516 --> 00:24:35.096 A:middle
But they were doing
it wrong as many times

00:24:35.096 --> 00:24:35.866 A:middle
as they were doing it right.

00:24:36.366 --> 00:24:38.666 A:middle
Or, for example, if they wanted
to say, "The boy is swimming,"

00:24:39.126 --> 00:24:40.446 A:middle
they would just pick
the word for "swim"

00:24:40.446 --> 00:24:41.526 A:middle
and they would pick
the word for "boy".

00:24:41.846 --> 00:24:44.776 A:middle
You know, they weren't really
creating these sentences.

00:24:44.776 --> 00:24:50.296 A:middle
You see, Avaz was very
successful at breaking

00:24:50.296 --> 00:24:55.726 A:middle
down this symbolism of words
and putting the concreteness

00:24:55.726 --> 00:24:56.836 A:middle
of pictures into that.

00:24:57.646 --> 00:25:00.586 A:middle
But this is actually a different
level of symbolism at play here.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:24:57.646 --> 00:25:00.586 A:middle
But this is actually a different
level of symbolism at play here.

00:25:00.586 --> 00:25:02.336 A:middle
This is a symbolism of grammar.

00:25:03.146 --> 00:25:06.616 A:middle
And grammar is something
that's so abstract,

00:25:06.616 --> 00:25:07.856 A:middle
and there are the
rules of grammar.

00:25:07.906 --> 00:25:09.876 A:middle
And those rules of
grammar are so abstract

00:25:09.876 --> 00:25:13.296 A:middle
that they're even very hard
for us as native speakers

00:25:13.296 --> 00:25:14.976 A:middle
to explain and to understand.

00:25:15.886 --> 00:25:18.026 A:middle
You know? For example, if
you take this sentence,

00:25:18.026 --> 00:25:20.996 A:middle
"I want to eat,"
what's the meaning

00:25:20.996 --> 00:25:22.816 A:middle
of the word "to"
in the sentence?

00:25:22.906 --> 00:25:25.686 A:middle
You know, if you asked me,
I wouldn't have an idea.

00:25:25.726 --> 00:25:27.386 A:middle
It's just a word that's there

00:25:27.386 --> 00:25:30.496 A:middle
because it's ungrammatical
if it wasn't there.

00:25:31.516 --> 00:25:33.726 A:middle
[ Laughter ]

00:25:34.226 --> 00:25:37.126 A:middle
If you take these sentences,
"The window broke," and,

00:25:37.126 --> 00:25:39.396 A:middle
"He broke the window,"
it's interesting, you know,

00:25:39.396 --> 00:25:41.396 A:middle
these two sentences are
both grammatically correct.

00:25:41.636 --> 00:25:43.926 A:middle
But the object that's
breaking is actually the same.

00:25:43.926 --> 00:25:45.746 A:middle
Right? The window is the
object that's breaking.

00:25:45.746 --> 00:25:49.466 A:middle
Why is it that it appears on one
side of "broke" on one sentence

00:25:49.466 --> 00:25:51.356 A:middle
and on the other side of
"broke" in the other sentence?

00:25:51.966 --> 00:25:56.146 A:middle
Or if you take this sentence,
"I eat," the past tense

00:25:56.146 --> 00:25:59.026 A:middle
of this is obviously, "I ate."

00:25:59.156 --> 00:26:01.706 A:middle
But if you negate this sentence,
if you say, "I didn't eat,"


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:25:59.156 --> 00:26:01.706 A:middle
But if you negate this sentence,
if you say, "I didn't eat,"

00:26:03.306 --> 00:26:05.796 A:middle
why is it wrong to
say, "I didn't ate"?

00:26:06.826 --> 00:26:11.926 A:middle
Right? So there are these
meta-rules at play here.

00:26:12.006 --> 00:26:15.586 A:middle
There are these things
that go beyond the rules

00:26:15.586 --> 00:26:18.306 A:middle
of which word presents
which meaning.

00:26:18.926 --> 00:26:20.466 A:middle
There are these meta-rules
of grammar.

00:26:21.056 --> 00:26:23.116 A:middle
And this was actually
very frustrating to us.

00:26:23.206 --> 00:26:28.026 A:middle
We went out behind the
pursuit Avaz with the intention

00:26:28.026 --> 00:26:30.356 A:middle
of giving communication,
full communication,

00:26:30.396 --> 00:26:32.396 A:middle
equal communication to
kids with disabilities.

00:26:32.726 --> 00:26:36.056 A:middle
And we knew that our mission
was actually being completely

00:26:36.056 --> 00:26:39.416 A:middle
underfulfilled if we were
only giving them words

00:26:39.646 --> 00:26:42.946 A:middle
without giving them the
ability to also create sentences

00:26:42.946 --> 00:26:44.046 A:middle
and to put these words together.

00:26:44.046 --> 00:26:47.446 A:middle
The problem was that,
unlike in the case of Avaz,

00:26:48.386 --> 00:26:50.166 A:middle
there was actually
very little research,

00:26:50.466 --> 00:26:53.946 A:middle
very little theory behind
how you can teach children

00:26:53.946 --> 00:26:55.636 A:middle
with autism grammar,
how you can teach them

00:26:55.636 --> 00:26:56.486 A:middle
to put words together.

00:26:57.076 --> 00:26:59.926 A:middle
We trawled through all of
the scientific journals.

00:26:59.926 --> 00:27:01.506 A:middle
We went to all of the
scientific conferences.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:26:59.926 --> 00:27:01.506 A:middle
We went to all of the
scientific conferences.

00:27:01.536 --> 00:27:03.416 A:middle
But very little insights
that people had got.

00:27:05.556 --> 00:27:09.816 A:middle
The insight that kind of
triggered a lot of ideas

00:27:09.816 --> 00:27:14.286 A:middle
in our head quite consistently
came from the work of somebody

00:27:14.286 --> 00:27:17.336 A:middle
who lived 2,500 years ago.

00:27:17.766 --> 00:27:19.756 A:middle
He was an Indian philosopher.

00:27:21.156 --> 00:27:23.976 A:middle
I don't know if he
exactly looks like this.

00:27:24.071 --> 00:27:26.071 A:middle
[ Laughter ]

00:27:26.126 --> 00:27:28.846 A:middle
The Indian government put out
a stamp about him in 2004.

00:27:29.026 --> 00:27:32.206 A:middle
He has the unfortunate
distinction of sharing his name

00:27:32.206 --> 00:27:33.106 A:middle
with a kind of sandwich.

00:27:33.106 --> 00:27:33.946 A:middle
It's called Panini.

00:27:34.031 --> 00:27:36.031 A:middle
[ Laughter ]

00:27:36.046 --> 00:27:41.906 A:middle
But Panini lived in -- it didn't
mean "sandwich" back then.

00:27:42.031 --> 00:27:44.031 A:middle
[ Laugther ]

00:27:44.046 --> 00:27:46.986 A:middle
Panini lived around 500 BC.

00:27:47.216 --> 00:27:49.446 A:middle
And Panini did something
which was phenomenal,

00:27:49.516 --> 00:27:51.886 A:middle
which is unprecedented
even today.

00:27:52.416 --> 00:27:55.736 A:middle
He took a language, the
language of Sanskrit,

00:27:57.206 --> 00:28:03.396 A:middle
and he created a concise,
complete, consistent set


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:27:57.206 --> 00:28:03.396 A:middle
and he created a concise,
complete, consistent set

00:28:03.396 --> 00:28:08.756 A:middle
of rules -- 4,000 rules -- that
described the entire language.

00:28:10.626 --> 00:28:14.736 A:middle
OK, so he had this set of 4,000
rules, and those rules are

00:28:14.796 --> 00:28:16.286 A:middle
of course still relevant today.

00:28:16.616 --> 00:28:20.586 A:middle
But with these 4,000 rules, if
you apply these 4,000 rules,

00:28:21.006 --> 00:28:23.496 A:middle
any sentence that you
created would be guaranteed

00:28:23.496 --> 00:28:25.066 A:middle
to be grammatically-correct
Sanskrit.

00:28:26.346 --> 00:28:28.686 A:middle
And conversely, any
grammatically-correct sentence

00:28:28.686 --> 00:28:32.326 A:middle
in Sanskrit, any sentence, any
book, any verbal reference,

00:28:32.326 --> 00:28:36.396 A:middle
any grammatically-correct
Sanskrit could be explained

00:28:36.766 --> 00:28:38.156 A:middle
with these 4,000 rules.

00:28:38.646 --> 00:28:40.916 A:middle
It was almost like he had
written a computer program

00:28:41.736 --> 00:28:42.986 A:middle
to generate Sanskrit.

00:28:43.496 --> 00:28:48.626 A:middle
So that codification of a
language and the way that he did

00:28:48.626 --> 00:28:50.156 A:middle
that was absolutely beautiful.

00:28:50.156 --> 00:28:51.306 A:middle
It was phenomenal.

00:28:51.566 --> 00:28:54.486 A:middle
But that codification of
Sanskrit gave us the first clue

00:28:54.916 --> 00:28:56.566 A:middle
that maybe this is an
approach that we can take.

00:28:56.566 --> 00:28:58.846 A:middle
Maybe we can codify the
rules of grammar and put it

00:28:58.846 --> 00:29:01.306 A:middle
into a computer in some
sense and see if we can use


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:28:58.846 --> 00:29:01.306 A:middle
into a computer in some
sense and see if we can use

00:29:01.306 --> 00:29:04.816 A:middle
that to give kids with
autism an access to grammar.

00:29:05.886 --> 00:29:08.186 A:middle
But even though we
had that insight,

00:29:09.136 --> 00:29:11.796 A:middle
the other missing component
was really the user experience.

00:29:11.796 --> 00:29:14.016 A:middle
How could we get kids to
interact with grammar?

00:29:14.836 --> 00:29:18.996 A:middle
And the answer to that really
appropriately came when I was

00:29:19.066 --> 00:29:22.716 A:middle
in a school for kids with autism
and I happened to interact

00:29:22.796 --> 00:29:26.376 A:middle
with -- I happened to
be present, you know,

00:29:26.376 --> 00:29:29.136 A:middle
where there was this little
girl, and there was her mother,

00:29:29.136 --> 00:29:30.236 A:middle
and there were her teachers.

00:29:30.926 --> 00:29:33.066 A:middle
And this girl, you
know, she had autism

00:29:33.066 --> 00:29:34.716 A:middle
and she was almost
completely nonverbal.

00:29:34.716 --> 00:29:35.986 A:middle
But once in a while,
she could speak.

00:29:36.556 --> 00:29:37.836 A:middle
And that's what happened
that day.

00:29:37.836 --> 00:29:41.246 A:middle
She jumped up and she
said the word "eat".

00:29:41.956 --> 00:29:43.426 A:middle
And there was no
context to this.

00:29:43.806 --> 00:29:45.296 A:middle
She just finished
eating her lunch,

00:29:45.426 --> 00:29:47.186 A:middle
so her teacher thought
perhaps she wanted

00:29:47.186 --> 00:29:48.276 A:middle
to talk about her lunch.

00:29:48.756 --> 00:29:51.296 A:middle
So they tried to get
her to communicate

00:29:51.296 --> 00:29:52.996 A:middle
about her lunch on Avaz.

00:29:52.996 --> 00:29:54.996 A:middle
But it was very clear
that, you know,

00:29:54.996 --> 00:29:56.266 A:middle
that was not what she
was trying to say.

00:29:57.206 --> 00:29:59.476 A:middle
So we were all standing
there and trying to figure

00:29:59.476 --> 00:30:01.566 A:middle
out what she meant
by the word "eat".


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:29:59.476 --> 00:30:01.566 A:middle
out what she meant
by the word "eat".

00:30:01.636 --> 00:30:05.006 A:middle
And then her mother started
asking her questions.

00:30:06.396 --> 00:30:08.816 A:middle
So her mother said,
"OK, eat what?

00:30:09.296 --> 00:30:09.956 A:middle
Eat lunch?

00:30:10.006 --> 00:30:10.656 A:middle
Eat breakfast?

00:30:10.746 --> 00:30:11.496 A:middle
Eat snacks?"

00:30:12.126 --> 00:30:14.936 A:middle
And then the girl took out her
iPad, and she took out Avaz

00:30:14.936 --> 00:30:16.416 A:middle
and she pointed to
the word "ice cream".

00:30:17.646 --> 00:30:19.596 A:middle
And then her mother
asked, "OK, who eats?

00:30:19.736 --> 00:30:21.576 A:middle
You eat? Someone else eats?"

00:30:21.986 --> 00:30:24.506 A:middle
You know? And then she
pointed to the word "I".

00:30:24.506 --> 00:30:27.356 A:middle
And then her mother
was like, "Eat when?

00:30:27.356 --> 00:30:28.256 A:middle
Eat now? Eat later?"

00:30:28.256 --> 00:30:31.106 A:middle
And it turned out that
this particular girl wanted

00:30:31.136 --> 00:30:33.616 A:middle
to eat ice cream on her
way back home from school.

00:30:34.636 --> 00:30:37.786 A:middle
Now it's not often that
I can pinpoint the moment

00:30:37.786 --> 00:30:39.376 A:middle
when the lightbulb
goes off in my head.

00:30:39.656 --> 00:30:42.836 A:middle
But in this particular case,
I remember this episode almost

00:30:42.836 --> 00:30:43.756 A:middle
like it happened yesterday.

00:30:44.706 --> 00:30:49.266 A:middle
Because what struck me was
that feeling of realization --

00:30:49.266 --> 00:30:53.416 A:middle
that realization that this
mother had gotten this girl

00:30:53.416 --> 00:30:56.966 A:middle
to communicate what she
wanted without using grammar.

00:30:58.616 --> 00:31:02.026 A:middle
I mean, this girl could not put
more than one word together.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:30:58.616 --> 00:31:02.026 A:middle
I mean, this girl could not put
more than one word together.

00:31:02.026 --> 00:31:04.366 A:middle
She could not put multiple words
together to create sentences.

00:31:04.436 --> 00:31:06.436 A:middle
She could not select
different forms of words.

00:31:06.736 --> 00:31:08.386 A:middle
She did not know what
the meaning of "to" was.

00:31:08.926 --> 00:31:12.846 A:middle
She did not know the way in
which English grammar worked.

00:31:12.846 --> 00:31:16.426 A:middle
It's almost as if her mother had
peered into her head and figured

00:31:16.426 --> 00:31:21.936 A:middle
out what the meaning was
that she wanted to convey.

00:31:21.936 --> 00:31:24.776 A:middle
So this was the other
part of the puzzle for me.

00:31:25.476 --> 00:31:27.386 A:middle
You know, and I took this idea

00:31:27.386 --> 00:31:31.056 A:middle
that we could really represent
meaning without grammar

00:31:31.516 --> 00:31:34.536 A:middle
if we joined words together
using questions and answers.

00:31:34.736 --> 00:31:37.886 A:middle
And I combined that with
the algorithms that came

00:31:37.886 --> 00:31:42.116 A:middle
from my study of Panini and all
of the resource in linguistics

00:31:42.116 --> 00:31:43.946 A:middle
and the resource in
neuroscience that had been

00:31:43.946 --> 00:31:44.936 A:middle
over the last few years.

00:31:45.646 --> 00:31:48.786 A:middle
And I put that together
to create an app.

00:31:48.786 --> 00:31:51.296 A:middle
It took me three years to
actually create this app.

00:31:51.296 --> 00:31:52.646 A:middle
I started in 2012.

00:31:52.646 --> 00:31:55.256 A:middle
It was in 2015 that the
pieces finally came together.

00:31:55.356 --> 00:31:59.716 A:middle
And in 2016, we put
this app out --

00:31:59.806 --> 00:32:01.166 A:middle
this year, just a
few months ago.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:31:59.806 --> 00:32:01.166 A:middle
this year, just a
few months ago.

00:32:02.086 --> 00:32:03.486 A:middle
It's called FreeSpeech.

00:32:04.076 --> 00:32:07.136 A:middle
And let me show you a quick
demo of FreeSpeech to explain

00:32:07.136 --> 00:32:08.866 A:middle
to you how we solved
this problem.

00:32:20.206 --> 00:32:21.936 A:middle
OK, so this is the
FreeSpeech App.

00:32:22.156 --> 00:32:25.146 A:middle
And you can see that it
has pictures the same way

00:32:25.146 --> 00:32:26.346 A:middle
that Avaz has pictures.

00:32:26.346 --> 00:32:29.146 A:middle
In fact, if I tap on the
More Words button here

00:32:29.146 --> 00:32:32.956 A:middle
on the bottom-left, it has all
of the pictures that Avaz has.

00:32:33.746 --> 00:32:36.406 A:middle
But unlike Avaz, when
you construct a sentence

00:32:36.406 --> 00:32:39.066 A:middle
in FreeSpeech, you
don't have to start

00:32:39.066 --> 00:32:40.456 A:middle
at the beginning
of the sentence.

00:32:40.456 --> 00:32:42.356 A:middle
In fact, you can start
anywhere in the sentence.

00:32:42.356 --> 00:32:45.586 A:middle
So, for example, supposing
I pick the word "take"

00:32:46.746 --> 00:32:48.726 A:middle
and I drop it here
on the screen.

00:32:49.176 --> 00:32:50.166 A:middle
Here's the interesting part.

00:32:50.376 --> 00:32:50.886 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Take

00:32:51.376 --> 00:32:55.626 A:middle
&gt;&gt; The app actually gives you
this lattice this scaffold

00:32:56.106 --> 00:32:59.236 A:middle
of questions around the word
that you've just dropped


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:33:00.086 --> 00:33:02.986 A:middle
so that you can add more words
to create a sentence out of it.

00:33:02.986 --> 00:33:05.666 A:middle
It's very similar to what
the girl's mother was doing.

00:33:05.666 --> 00:33:08.886 A:middle
For example, if I drag
the word "teacher"

00:33:09.086 --> 00:33:11.706 A:middle
and I put it into
the word "who".

00:33:12.186 --> 00:33:13.416 A:middle
&gt;&gt; The teacher takes.

00:33:13.786 --> 00:33:15.856 A:middle
&gt;&gt; It automatically
constructs a sentence

00:33:16.256 --> 00:33:17.706 A:middle
with that specific meaning.

00:33:17.706 --> 00:33:18.806 A:middle
It says, "The teacher takes."

00:33:19.306 --> 00:33:22.506 A:middle
I can take the word "book", and
if I put it into the "what",

00:33:22.816 --> 00:33:25.496 A:middle
it will say, "The
teacher takes the book."

00:33:25.696 --> 00:33:29.186 A:middle
And if I take the word "school"
and if I drop it on the word

00:33:29.286 --> 00:33:34.506 A:middle
"to", it will say, "The teacher
takes the book to the school."

00:33:35.286 --> 00:33:38.076 A:middle
Let me show you a slightly
more complicated example.

00:33:38.326 --> 00:33:41.306 A:middle
So, supposing we pick the
word "want", and let's put

00:33:41.306 --> 00:33:44.376 A:middle
that in here, it pops up
all of these questions.

00:33:45.386 --> 00:33:49.026 A:middle
And I can take the word "parent"
and I put it into the "who".

00:33:49.026 --> 00:33:50.636 A:middle
If I put into "want",
for example,

00:33:50.636 --> 00:33:52.326 A:middle
it will say, "Want the parent."

00:33:52.506 --> 00:33:55.896 A:middle
But if I took that from that
location and if I put it

00:33:55.896 --> 00:33:58.526 A:middle
into the "who", it will
say, "The parent wants."

00:33:58.526 --> 00:34:00.146 A:middle
And you see that every
time you add a word,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:33:58.526 --> 00:34:00.146 A:middle
And you see that every
time you add a word,

00:34:00.236 --> 00:34:02.366 A:middle
it actually gives you
even more questions.

00:34:02.366 --> 00:34:03.496 A:middle
So more questions pop up.

00:34:03.496 --> 00:34:05.276 A:middle
So you can see that
there's a "whose"

00:34:05.276 --> 00:34:07.346 A:middle
which is next to "parent".

00:34:07.346 --> 00:34:09.766 A:middle
So if I tap that, it will
ask you the question,

00:34:09.766 --> 00:34:10.666 A:middle
"Whose parent wants?"

00:34:10.666 --> 00:34:13.116 A:middle
And then I can drag the
word "she", for example,

00:34:13.116 --> 00:34:14.485 A:middle
and drop that in here.

00:34:14.485 --> 00:34:16.386 A:middle
It will say, "Her parent wants."

00:34:16.835 --> 00:34:20.036 A:middle
If I tap this little button on
the top-left corner of "parent",

00:34:20.036 --> 00:34:21.755 A:middle
I can convert that
into a plural.

00:34:21.755 --> 00:34:24.206 A:middle
So I can make it,
"Her parents want."

00:34:24.815 --> 00:34:28.416 A:middle
If I add the word "see",
for example, I can say,

00:34:28.416 --> 00:34:30.866 A:middle
"Her parents want to see."

00:34:30.866 --> 00:34:33.516 A:middle
And I can drag the word
"you" and I can make it,

00:34:33.516 --> 00:34:35.216 A:middle
"Her parents want to see you."

00:34:36.096 --> 00:34:38.005 A:middle
In fact, I can do even more
complicated things here.

00:34:38.146 --> 00:34:41.226 A:middle
I can say that all of
this happened in the past.

00:34:41.485 --> 00:34:43.806 A:middle
And I don't have to use the
rules of grammar to do this.

00:34:43.866 --> 00:34:45.416 A:middle
All I can do is I
can tap the button

00:34:45.416 --> 00:34:46.356 A:middle
at the bottom that says Past.

00:34:46.356 --> 00:34:50.636 A:middle
It will say, "Her parents
wanted to see you."

00:34:51.045 --> 00:34:52.016 A:middle
And I can negate that.

00:34:52.016 --> 00:34:54.576 A:middle
So if I press the Not button
at the bottom, it will say,

00:34:54.576 --> 00:34:57.166 A:middle
"Her parents didn't
want to see you."

00:34:57.816 --> 00:34:59.176 A:middle
I can make a question out of it.

00:34:59.176 --> 00:35:01.276 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Didn't her parents
didn't want to see you.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:34:59.176 --> 00:35:01.276 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Didn't her parents
didn't want to see you.

00:35:01.276 --> 00:35:03.956 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Or I can make even more
complicated questions.

00:35:04.516 --> 00:35:06.586 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:35:07.086 --> 00:35:08.976 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Why didn't her
parents want to see you.

00:35:09.516 --> 00:35:11.546 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:35:12.046 --> 00:35:12.346 A:middle
Thank you.

00:35:13.616 --> 00:35:13.986 A:middle
Thank you.

00:35:14.366 --> 00:35:15.616 A:middle
So that's how FreeSpeech works.

00:35:15.616 --> 00:35:17.216 A:middle
And FreeSpeech is pretty amazing

00:35:17.826 --> 00:35:20.056 A:middle
because I think it's
the very first time

00:35:20.056 --> 00:35:23.056 A:middle
that someone has actually come
up with a grammar predictor.

00:35:23.956 --> 00:35:25.176 A:middle
That's what the app
is doing, right?

00:35:25.176 --> 00:35:26.866 A:middle
I mean, you have all of
these different pictures

00:35:26.866 --> 00:35:29.246 A:middle
and the app is putting
grammar around it.

00:35:29.976 --> 00:35:32.026 A:middle
Now why is that important
for kids with autism?

00:35:32.426 --> 00:35:35.506 A:middle
The best way to kind of explain
that is to draw an analogy

00:35:35.506 --> 00:35:36.656 A:middle
to a different disability.

00:35:36.786 --> 00:35:39.126 A:middle
I'm sure many of you here
have heard of dyslexia.

00:35:39.506 --> 00:35:40.666 A:middle
Some of you may have
even struggled

00:35:40.666 --> 00:35:41.506 A:middle
with it when you were kids.

00:35:42.086 --> 00:35:44.546 A:middle
Kids with dyslexia have a lot
of difficulty with spelling.

00:35:44.976 --> 00:35:46.556 A:middle
You know, English
spelling is horrible.

00:35:46.616 --> 00:35:48.376 A:middle
I have difficulty
with English spelling.

00:35:49.116 --> 00:35:51.996 A:middle
But if you give a kid
with dyslexia an iPad

00:35:51.996 --> 00:35:54.086 A:middle
and you ask them to type,

00:35:55.206 --> 00:35:57.336 A:middle
magically their disability
goes away.

00:35:57.706 --> 00:36:00.076 A:middle
Why? Because of spell check.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:35:57.706 --> 00:36:00.076 A:middle
Why? Because of spell check.

00:36:00.226 --> 00:36:01.116 A:middle
Because of autocorrect.

00:36:02.206 --> 00:36:05.056 A:middle
So a kid with dyslexia who
is typing on an iPad is able

00:36:05.056 --> 00:36:08.236 A:middle
to communicate, is able to type
perfectly correct English even

00:36:08.236 --> 00:36:09.516 A:middle
though they have
difficulties with spelling.

00:36:09.516 --> 00:36:12.306 A:middle
Avaz does exactly that for kids

00:36:12.306 --> 00:36:14.836 A:middle
who have a language
disability like autism.

00:36:15.676 --> 00:36:17.446 A:middle
It plays to their strengths.

00:36:17.806 --> 00:36:20.456 A:middle
They're able to take
pictures, they're able to pick

00:36:20.456 --> 00:36:26.176 A:middle
out pictures from the tablet,
and they're able to put pictures

00:36:26.176 --> 00:36:28.016 A:middle
in different configurations.

00:36:28.706 --> 00:36:29.666 A:middle
But every time they do that,

00:36:30.116 --> 00:36:33.746 A:middle
the algorithm is automatically
creating a perfectly-grammatical

00:36:33.746 --> 00:36:36.906 A:middle
sentence and is speaking
that out.

00:36:37.976 --> 00:36:41.516 A:middle
Now, we did trials for about
an entire year before we put

00:36:42.576 --> 00:36:43.926 A:middle
FreeSpeech out on the market.

00:36:44.426 --> 00:36:46.256 A:middle
And the results with kids

00:36:46.256 --> 00:36:48.306 A:middle
with autism were dramatic
-- truly dramatic.

00:36:48.416 --> 00:36:50.856 A:middle
There were kids who were
communicating with no words

00:36:50.856 --> 00:36:52.306 A:middle
or they were communicating
with one word.

00:36:52.786 --> 00:36:54.246 A:middle
And suddenly, in minutes --

00:36:54.296 --> 00:36:56.346 A:middle
literally minutes after they
started using the app --

00:36:56.396 --> 00:36:58.766 A:middle
they were constructing these
four or five-word sentences.

00:36:58.836 --> 00:37:01.566 A:middle
In fact, there was this
one particular kid --


WEBVTT
