00:39:04.286 --> 00:39:05.726 A:middle
in speech therapy in autism.

00:39:06.236 --> 00:39:13.116 A:middle
In fact, when we put
FreeSpeech out, you know,

00:39:13.376 --> 00:39:15.206 A:middle
Lucas also had a
very interesting idea

00:39:16.076 --> 00:39:18.226 A:middle
because Lucas had this
other kid on his caseload.

00:39:18.456 --> 00:39:21.346 A:middle
And this other kid had a --
you know, he was an Avaz user

00:39:21.346 --> 00:39:23.436 A:middle
but he was facing a very
different kind of problem.

00:39:24.296 --> 00:39:25.796 A:middle
This other kid that was

00:39:25.796 --> 00:39:28.836 A:middle
on Lucas' caseload,
he was bilingual.

00:39:29.026 --> 00:39:31.796 A:middle
He came from a bilingual
family --

00:39:31.986 --> 00:39:33.416 A:middle
bilingual, English and Spanish.

00:39:34.136 --> 00:39:36.846 A:middle
So, at school, he would
be learning in English.

00:39:36.906 --> 00:39:38.456 A:middle
All of his teachers would
talk to him in English.

00:39:38.486 --> 00:39:42.916 A:middle
But when he went back home, his
family, and all of his friends,

00:39:42.916 --> 00:39:44.896 A:middle
and all of his neighbors, they
would be speaking in Spanish.

00:39:46.376 --> 00:39:50.156 A:middle
Now this is a challenge that
speech therapists have battled

00:39:50.156 --> 00:39:52.096 A:middle
with for many, many years.

00:39:52.246 --> 00:39:55.486 A:middle
You know, devices like Avaz,
apps like Avaz do exist.

00:39:55.486 --> 00:39:56.906 A:middle
They do exist in
different languages.

00:39:57.616 --> 00:40:00.806 A:middle
But the problem of how do
you give a voice to somebody


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:39:57.616 --> 00:40:00.806 A:middle
But the problem of how do
you give a voice to somebody

00:40:00.806 --> 00:40:03.516 A:middle
who speaks two different
languages has always been a

00:40:03.516 --> 00:40:06.026 A:middle
challenge for kids with autism

00:40:06.026 --> 00:40:08.136 A:middle
and for the therapists
that work with them.

00:40:08.686 --> 00:40:12.166 A:middle
So, let me give you a short demo
of why exactly that's a problem.

00:40:12.166 --> 00:40:15.616 A:middle
Let me go back into
Avaz and explain

00:40:15.616 --> 00:40:19.606 A:middle
to you what the issue is.

00:40:19.606 --> 00:40:20.586 A:middle
So, this is Avaz, right?

00:40:20.586 --> 00:40:22.336 A:middle
So we looked at the
-- I'm just going

00:40:22.336 --> 00:40:24.136 A:middle
to create a very quick sentence.

00:40:24.136 --> 00:40:28.656 A:middle
I'm going to say, "I want
to," and I go to Actions.

00:40:28.656 --> 00:40:29.916 A:middle
And let's say, "I
want to go home."

00:40:30.026 --> 00:40:33.676 A:middle
Right? So I pick out these
different words here.

00:40:34.026 --> 00:40:36.656 A:middle
And so let's say that a kid
is able to make this sentence,

00:40:36.656 --> 00:40:38.476 A:middle
"I want to go home,"
and they can speak it.

00:40:38.696 --> 00:40:42.976 A:middle
Now there is a Spanish
version of Avaz available,

00:40:42.976 --> 00:40:45.666 A:middle
so let me switch into
that very quickly.

00:40:46.346 --> 00:40:49.096 A:middle
So -- yeah.

00:40:49.846 --> 00:40:52.786 A:middle
How many Spanish
speakers in the audience?

00:40:53.526 --> 00:40:55.816 A:middle
OK. I don't know Spanish at all.

00:40:55.816 --> 00:40:56.906 A:middle
I know zero Spanish.

00:40:57.136 --> 00:41:01.176 A:middle
But, you know, I'm going
to try to use the pictures


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:40:57.136 --> 00:41:01.176 A:middle
But, you know, I'm going
to try to use the pictures

00:41:01.696 --> 00:41:04.656 A:middle
to create a Spanish sentence
of exactly the same thing.

00:41:05.036 --> 00:41:06.036 A:middle
So, let's see.

00:41:06.036 --> 00:41:07.596 A:middle
So I have the picture
for the word "I".

00:41:07.976 --> 00:41:09.056 A:middle
I can recognize that.

00:41:09.056 --> 00:41:09.516 A:middle
That's here.

00:41:09.516 --> 00:41:11.796 A:middle
And then I have "want".

00:41:12.246 --> 00:41:15.606 A:middle
And this looks like the
picture for the word "to".

00:41:16.356 --> 00:41:17.746 A:middle
And this is "go".

00:41:18.496 --> 00:41:21.166 A:middle
And so there's places in here.

00:41:21.166 --> 00:41:24.646 A:middle
And this is "home".

00:41:26.116 --> 00:41:29.916 A:middle
Is that the right
sentence in Spanish?

00:41:29.916 --> 00:41:34.416 A:middle
If I went to Mexico and if I
said this, a kid would laugh

00:41:34.416 --> 00:41:37.106 A:middle
at me because this is
completely grammatically wrong.

00:41:38.406 --> 00:41:40.616 A:middle
You see, I've actually
done a pretty good job

00:41:40.616 --> 00:41:42.746 A:middle
of picking the right
words out the words --

00:41:42.746 --> 00:41:44.626 A:middle
the words "I", "want", "go".

00:41:44.626 --> 00:41:45.506 A:middle
All of these are correct.

00:41:46.176 --> 00:41:49.646 A:middle
But in Spanish, the way that the
words work is very different.

00:41:49.646 --> 00:41:54.126 A:middle
For example, the word "querer"
-- the word that means "want" --

00:41:54.606 --> 00:41:57.006 A:middle
you actually have to inflect
that so it becomes "quiero"

00:41:57.546 --> 00:41:59.806 A:middle
when you use it for
the word "I".


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:42:00.456 --> 00:42:02.196 A:middle
And similarly, you
don't use the word "tu"

00:42:02.456 --> 00:42:04.736 A:middle
in Spanish the same way that
you use it with English.

00:42:04.736 --> 00:42:06.416 A:middle
You'd actually put that
word before the word

00:42:06.476 --> 00:42:09.046 A:middle
"casa" to say "tu home".

00:42:09.566 --> 00:42:12.736 A:middle
So the problem here is
that when you switch

00:42:12.736 --> 00:42:14.176 A:middle
between two different languages,

00:42:14.176 --> 00:42:15.886 A:middle
the interface actually
looks very similar.

00:42:15.886 --> 00:42:16.856 A:middle
And you can see that, right?

00:42:17.006 --> 00:42:18.926 A:middle
The Avaz interface
looks almost identical

00:42:18.926 --> 00:42:20.186 A:middle
between the two languages.

00:42:21.126 --> 00:42:24.106 A:middle
But the user experience is
actually completely different

00:42:24.196 --> 00:42:26.626 A:middle
because kids have to learn
completely different patterns

00:42:26.626 --> 00:42:28.326 A:middle
to be able to construct
these sentences

00:42:28.326 --> 00:42:29.586 A:middle
and to be able to
put them together.

00:42:30.386 --> 00:42:35.336 A:middle
So this was a problem that
not just my friend, Lucas,

00:42:35.336 --> 00:42:37.486 A:middle
but really everyone
who was working

00:42:37.486 --> 00:42:38.486 A:middle
with kids with disabilities.

00:42:38.796 --> 00:42:42.846 A:middle
Essentially, the child had to
learn two different patterns

00:42:43.126 --> 00:42:46.016 A:middle
of using the same app for them
to be able to communicate.

00:42:47.206 --> 00:42:49.326 A:middle
So the idea that kind of
went off in our heads was,

00:42:49.326 --> 00:42:51.556 A:middle
"Can we use FreeSpeech
to be able to do this?"

00:42:52.226 --> 00:42:54.266 A:middle
FreeSpeech is essentially,
in some sense,

00:42:54.346 --> 00:42:56.376 A:middle
a representation of meaning.

00:42:56.376 --> 00:42:58.176 A:middle
Right? So the way that you
put these words together,

00:42:58.176 --> 00:42:59.816 A:middle
the way that you
construct these sentences,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:43:00.306 --> 00:43:02.436 A:middle
they're essentially
conveying what the meaning is

00:43:02.436 --> 00:43:03.526 A:middle
that you're trying to say.

00:43:03.686 --> 00:43:05.376 A:middle
And the app is putting
the words together.

00:43:05.376 --> 00:43:09.416 A:middle
So can we use that to be able to
help kids construct sentences,

00:43:09.416 --> 00:43:12.086 A:middle
you know, even if they
have a different language?

00:43:12.086 --> 00:43:13.416 A:middle
So I'm going to go
into the Settings here,

00:43:13.416 --> 00:43:14.976 A:middle
and there's a Spanish
setting here.

00:43:15.756 --> 00:43:17.976 A:middle
And you can see that,
when you do that,

00:43:17.976 --> 00:43:20.126 A:middle
the interface completely
changes into Spanish.

00:43:21.596 --> 00:43:23.756 A:middle
And all the words
are in Spanish.

00:43:24.356 --> 00:43:26.366 A:middle
The labels are in
Spanish and everything.

00:43:26.506 --> 00:43:28.996 A:middle
And when I drag a word
and I put it in here,

00:43:28.996 --> 00:43:32.486 A:middle
all of the interface elements
here are in Spanish as well.

00:43:32.846 --> 00:43:36.056 A:middle
The questions are in Spanish,
the tenses, everything.

00:43:36.586 --> 00:43:37.606 A:middle
But here's the interesting part.

00:43:37.946 --> 00:43:39.796 A:middle
When I start putting words in,

00:43:40.456 --> 00:43:41.116 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I want.

00:43:41.686 --> 00:43:44.586 A:middle
&gt;&gt; It actually gives me an
English sentence as the output.

00:43:45.096 --> 00:43:49.866 A:middle
So I can say -- so if I want to
try to make the same sentence,

00:43:50.146 --> 00:43:52.016 A:middle
I can take the same words

00:43:52.016 --> 00:43:53.116 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I want to go.

00:43:53.116 --> 00:43:54.666 A:middle
&gt;&gt; And I can put that in here.

00:43:54.836 --> 00:43:58.246 A:middle
And I'm following exactly
the same user interface.

00:43:58.246 --> 00:43:59.356 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I want to go home.

00:43:59.356 --> 00:44:01.286 A:middle
&gt;&gt; But I'm creating a
sentence in another language.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:43:59.356 --> 00:44:01.286 A:middle
&gt;&gt; But I'm creating a
sentence in another language.

00:44:03.286 --> 00:44:03.976 A:middle
You know, the --

00:44:04.516 --> 00:44:08.546 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:44:09.046 --> 00:44:12.746 A:middle
So we put this out, you
know, only a few weeks ago

00:44:12.856 --> 00:44:15.176 A:middle
and we're already getting
some reports of people

00:44:15.176 --> 00:44:18.846 A:middle
who found this quite useful, not
in a special-education classroom

00:44:18.846 --> 00:44:21.156 A:middle
with a disability, but in a
special-education classroom

00:44:21.576 --> 00:44:24.066 A:middle
for ELL -- for English
Language Learners --

00:44:24.496 --> 00:44:27.596 A:middle
and kids who are in
schools in America

00:44:27.596 --> 00:44:29.726 A:middle
who are entering the
American education system

00:44:29.726 --> 00:44:30.786 A:middle
without knowing English.

00:44:31.486 --> 00:44:33.186 A:middle
There are teachers who
are experimenting to see

00:44:33.186 --> 00:44:36.406 A:middle
if they can do this with those
kids to teach them English.

00:44:37.066 --> 00:44:41.356 A:middle
So could you use FreeSpeech
to teach someone English?

00:44:41.846 --> 00:44:43.416 A:middle
Or, for that matter,
could you use FreeSpeech

00:44:43.456 --> 00:44:45.916 A:middle
to teach anyone a new language?

00:44:47.386 --> 00:44:49.096 A:middle
Let me show you something else.

00:44:50.686 --> 00:44:53.516 A:middle
You know, I'm going to go into
the app now, and I'm going

00:44:53.516 --> 00:44:59.936 A:middle
to go back into the Settings
and I'm going to pick Chinese.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:45:00.526 --> 00:45:02.676 A:middle
How many Chinese-speakers
do we have in the audience?

00:45:03.666 --> 00:45:05.086 A:middle
Oh, OK. All right.

00:45:05.536 --> 00:45:07.226 A:middle
Well, typically when
I give these demos,

00:45:07.226 --> 00:45:09.976 A:middle
I try to pick a language that
nobody in the audience knows.

00:45:10.286 --> 00:45:12.286 A:middle
[ Laugther ]

00:45:12.556 --> 00:45:15.096 A:middle
Unfortunately, WWDC is a
little too international

00:45:15.096 --> 00:45:17.326 A:middle
for that trick to work for us.

00:45:17.436 --> 00:45:18.666 A:middle
I'll just keep my
fingers crossed.

00:45:18.666 --> 00:45:21.416 A:middle
You can see that the
interface has changed

00:45:21.496 --> 00:45:23.066 A:middle
to Chinese now the
way that it changed

00:45:23.066 --> 00:45:24.526 A:middle
to Spanish the last
time I did that.

00:45:25.136 --> 00:45:27.586 A:middle
But there's something very
interesting that's going

00:45:27.586 --> 00:45:28.166 A:middle
to happen now.

00:45:28.166 --> 00:45:29.516 A:middle
So I'm going to take words out.

00:45:29.566 --> 00:45:32.966 A:middle
So let's pick the word
"want" and put it in here.

00:45:39.216 --> 00:45:40.146 A:middle
Can you see what's happening?

00:45:40.236 --> 00:45:48.196 A:middle
It's actually creating
a sentence.

00:45:48.376 --> 00:45:51.106 A:middle
It's actually creating a
sentence not in English

00:45:51.226 --> 00:45:53.226 A:middle
but in English and in Chinese.

00:45:53.846 --> 00:45:57.186 A:middle
And I can do all of the things
that I did with English.

00:45:57.186 --> 00:46:02.316 A:middle
For example, I can say,
"That happened in the past."


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:45:57.186 --> 00:46:02.316 A:middle
For example, I can say,
"That happened in the past."

00:46:02.316 --> 00:46:04.866 A:middle
I can say, "It didn't happen."

00:46:05.736 --> 00:46:08.316 A:middle
And that's how you can
actually construct sentences

00:46:08.316 --> 00:46:10.226 A:middle
in a completely different
language using

00:46:10.226 --> 00:46:11.376 A:middle
FreeSpeech interface.

00:46:12.516 --> 00:46:20.546 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:46:21.046 --> 00:46:22.506 A:middle
Could you use this
to learn Chinese?

00:46:23.306 --> 00:46:27.456 A:middle
Or, vice versa, can
Chinese people use this

00:46:27.456 --> 00:46:28.326 A:middle
to learn English?

00:46:29.816 --> 00:46:31.496 A:middle
That's an experiment
that we did.

00:46:31.876 --> 00:46:33.316 A:middle
I was in China in May.

00:46:33.716 --> 00:46:38.176 A:middle
And I went to China and I tried
to see if we could get kids

00:46:38.176 --> 00:46:40.006 A:middle
in China to start
using FreeSpeech

00:46:40.046 --> 00:46:41.036 A:middle
to learn English instead.

00:46:41.036 --> 00:46:43.456 A:middle
And I want to show
you a short video

00:46:44.066 --> 00:46:47.956 A:middle
of an experience that we had.

00:46:48.816 --> 00:46:50.506 A:middle
So this is a school in Shanghai.

00:46:50.756 --> 00:46:53.816 A:middle
You can see the kids are
playing with FreeSpeech.

00:46:54.516 --> 00:47:10.546 A:middle
[ Foreign Language ]


WEBVTT
