00:46:54.516 --> 00:47:10.546 A:middle
[ Foreign Language ]

00:47:11.046 --> 00:47:13.106 A:middle
They're having an
incredible amount of fun.

00:47:13.106 --> 00:47:13.966 A:middle
The kid loves the iPad.

00:47:14.516 --> 00:47:19.976 A:middle
[ Foreign Language ]

00:47:20.476 --> 00:47:20.976 A:middle
They're killing it, right?

00:47:21.516 --> 00:47:26.856 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:47:27.356 --> 00:47:32.096 A:middle
So, that's the next big
project that we're working on.

00:47:32.306 --> 00:47:36.386 A:middle
And we're trying to create
a game that uses FreeSpeech

00:47:36.386 --> 00:47:40.856 A:middle
at its heart to teach language
to kids that are trying

00:47:40.856 --> 00:47:43.116 A:middle
to learn a new language,
particularly kids

00:47:43.116 --> 00:47:43.966 A:middle
that are trying to
learn English.

00:47:43.966 --> 00:47:47.056 A:middle
You know, it's very interesting.

00:47:47.056 --> 00:47:51.806 A:middle
There was a study that
was published, you know,

00:47:51.806 --> 00:47:53.256 A:middle
about five or six years ago.

00:47:53.546 --> 00:47:58.936 A:middle
Of all people, it was
published by the NSA.

00:47:58.936 --> 00:48:03.246 A:middle
So there was this spy
master probably in the NSA


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:47:58.936 --> 00:48:03.246 A:middle
So there was this spy
master probably in the NSA

00:48:03.246 --> 00:48:04.486 A:middle
who did this very
interesting study.

00:48:04.486 --> 00:48:07.696 A:middle
He took a bunch of the
world's languages and he tried

00:48:07.696 --> 00:48:11.116 A:middle
to sort them, he tried to
order them in the order

00:48:11.116 --> 00:48:13.156 A:middle
of which language is
the most difficult

00:48:13.756 --> 00:48:15.296 A:middle
for an English-speaker to speak.

00:48:15.296 --> 00:48:18.356 A:middle
Which one do you
think came out on top?

00:48:19.516 --> 00:48:25.626 A:middle
[ Laughter ]

00:48:26.126 --> 00:48:27.426 A:middle
Well, number 3 was Arabic.

00:48:28.656 --> 00:48:29.506 A:middle
Any Arabic speakers?

00:48:31.296 --> 00:48:32.686 A:middle
Number 2 was Korean.

00:48:33.766 --> 00:48:36.686 A:middle
And number 1 was Japanese.

00:48:38.526 --> 00:48:39.776 A:middle
Any Japanese speakers here?

00:48:40.896 --> 00:48:41.926 A:middle
OK, wow. All right.

00:48:42.526 --> 00:48:45.976 A:middle
So, the native Japanese
speakers here, congratulations.

00:48:46.196 --> 00:48:48.506 A:middle
The NSA thinks yours is the most
difficult language to learn.

00:48:48.506 --> 00:48:49.986 A:middle
And by the time you
were three years old,

00:48:50.346 --> 00:48:51.896 A:middle
you were speaking
Japanese fluently.

00:48:52.286 --> 00:48:58.016 A:middle
You know, why do kids
learn language so easily?

00:48:58.016 --> 00:48:59.956 A:middle
It always frustrates me.

00:48:59.956 --> 00:49:01.356 A:middle
It always makes me very jealous.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:48:59.956 --> 00:49:01.356 A:middle
It always makes me very jealous.

00:49:01.356 --> 00:49:02.316 A:middle
You know, I have a little son.

00:49:02.316 --> 00:49:03.326 A:middle
He's one and a half years old.

00:49:03.756 --> 00:49:07.556 A:middle
And I know that in another
one and a half years,

00:49:07.886 --> 00:49:11.106 A:middle
he'll be speaking
completely fluently.

00:49:11.106 --> 00:49:14.106 A:middle
And it's always been
a source of puzzlement

00:49:14.106 --> 00:49:15.426 A:middle
to me in why they do that.

00:49:15.966 --> 00:49:18.586 A:middle
What the theory says
-- what the theory

00:49:18.586 --> 00:49:19.766 A:middle
of language acquisition says --

00:49:19.766 --> 00:49:22.886 A:middle
is that kids learn a
language much faster

00:49:22.886 --> 00:49:25.336 A:middle
and much more effectively
than adults

00:49:25.336 --> 00:49:26.696 A:middle
because they're immersed in it.

00:49:27.196 --> 00:49:30.696 A:middle
You know, they hear it,
they try to speak it,

00:49:31.106 --> 00:49:33.386 A:middle
and they know what the meaning
is of what's being said to them

00:49:33.386 --> 00:49:35.046 A:middle
because they understand
the context

00:49:35.046 --> 00:49:35.876 A:middle
in which it's being said.

00:49:37.206 --> 00:49:39.566 A:middle
What if we could
simulate emotion

00:49:39.566 --> 00:49:43.836 A:middle
and provide the same capability
to adults and older children?

00:49:44.996 --> 00:49:47.966 A:middle
That's why I'm excited about
the prospect of FreeSpeech.

00:49:47.966 --> 00:49:49.986 A:middle
Because with FreeSpeech,
you're making these sentences,

00:49:50.266 --> 00:49:51.516 A:middle
and you know what the meaning is

00:49:51.516 --> 00:49:53.116 A:middle
because you're using
pictures as a bridge.

00:49:53.866 --> 00:49:56.296 A:middle
And every time you make
sentences in FreeSpeech,

00:49:56.806 --> 00:49:59.126 A:middle
the app is telling you
what the sentence means

00:49:59.476 --> 00:50:00.946 A:middle
in the language you're
trying to learn.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:49:59.476 --> 00:50:00.946 A:middle
in the language you're
trying to learn.

00:50:00.946 --> 00:50:03.856 A:middle
That's the interesting thing,

00:50:03.856 --> 00:50:05.656 A:middle
and that's what we're
working on.

00:50:07.076 --> 00:50:10.396 A:middle
You know, language is something

00:50:10.396 --> 00:50:13.566 A:middle
which is really interesting
for multiple reasons.

00:50:14.126 --> 00:50:19.476 A:middle
In this connected world
where anyone anywhere

00:50:19.476 --> 00:50:23.546 A:middle
in the world is two clicks away
on Facebook or on WhatsApp,

00:50:24.506 --> 00:50:26.386 A:middle
language is really
the last barrier

00:50:26.386 --> 00:50:27.556 A:middle
that we have as a species.

00:50:28.356 --> 00:50:29.586 A:middle
I mean, think about it.

00:50:29.586 --> 00:50:32.096 A:middle
Right? How many of
you have a friend

00:50:32.726 --> 00:50:34.736 A:middle
with whom you don't
share any language?

00:50:36.956 --> 00:50:40.636 A:middle
You know, communication
is the fundamental barrier

00:50:40.636 --> 00:50:42.656 A:middle
that children with
disabilities are born with.

00:50:42.656 --> 00:50:46.446 A:middle
But it's also the last barrier
that we have to cross as people.

00:50:46.446 --> 00:50:48.786 A:middle
And that's why the
work that I do is

00:50:48.786 --> 00:50:50.716 A:middle
so satisfying and
exciting to me.

00:50:51.546 --> 00:50:55.436 A:middle
You know, I build apps that
help kids with disabilities,

00:50:55.746 --> 00:51:00.206 A:middle
kids with disadvantaged
education backgrounds, refugees.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:50:55.746 --> 00:51:00.206 A:middle
kids with disadvantaged
education backgrounds, refugees.

00:51:00.206 --> 00:51:04.306 A:middle
You know, I build apps
that use Apple's devices

00:51:04.306 --> 00:51:05.816 A:middle
to make the lives of
these people better.

00:51:06.616 --> 00:51:08.026 A:middle
But I'm hopeful that
some of the work

00:51:08.026 --> 00:51:12.186 A:middle
that I'm doing could
also help all of us look

00:51:12.186 --> 00:51:14.556 A:middle
with a different light and
with a different appreciation

00:51:15.016 --> 00:51:18.366 A:middle
at the most beautiful,
most expressive

00:51:18.806 --> 00:51:21.016 A:middle
of human inventions -- language.

00:51:22.056 --> 00:51:22.396 A:middle
Thank you.

00:51:23.516 --> 00:51:29.500 A:middle
[ Applause ]

